The manufacturing, selling and possession of '''Cannabis''' is illegal in [[Trinidad and Tobago]].

== History ==

In 1915 Trinidad created the [[Ganja Ordinance]], by which all cannabis sold on the island was gathered into bonded warehouses and distributed only to sellers who paid a license fee, similar to the system found in Bengal.<ref name="Mills2003">{{cite book|author=James H. Mills|title=Cannabis Britannica: Empire, Trade, and Prohibition 1800-1928|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gMhaD7iuF8gC&pg=PA139|date=11 September 2003|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-155465-0|pages=139–}}</ref> Cannabis was banned in the islands in 1925.<ref name="KleinDay2004">{{cite book|author1=Axel Klein|author2=Marcus Day|author3=Anthony Harriott|title=Caribbean Drugs: From Criminalization to Harm Reduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KlJyez-Nr70C&pg=PA58|date=13 November 2004|publisher=Zed Books|isbn=978-1-84277-499-1|pages=58–}}</ref> In 2018, the head of the [[Caribbean Collective for Justice]] has called for the nation to decriminalize cannabis.<ref>http://www.looptt.com/content/tt-petition-decriminalisation-marijuana-gathers-momentum</ref>

