{{advert|date=June 2016}} {{Infobox Organization |name = Children's Food Trust |image = Children's Food Trust.png |size = |caption = |abbreviation = |formation = 2005 |dissolved = 2017 |status = [[Charitable organization|Charity]] |purpose = Works with childcare providers, schools, local authorities, community organisations and industry to improve the food that children eat |location = 3rd Floor, 1 East Parade [[Sheffield]], [[United Kingdom|UK]] |region_served = UK |membership = |leader_title = Chair |leader_name = Adam Starkey, Linda Cregan |main_organ = Board |affiliations = [[The Prince's Trust]]{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}, [[Local Authority Catering Association]]{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} |budget = |website = {{url|http://www.childrensfoodtrust.org.uk}} }}
The '''Children's Food Trust''' (formerly the '''School Food Trust''', renamed in 2012) was a [[Charitable organization|charity]] in the United Kingdom that sought to promote healthy eating for children.
==History== The Trust - originally named the School Food Trust - was created as a [[non-departmental public body]] in 2005 by the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]] (DfES), following [[celebrity chef]] [[Jamie Oliver]]'s critique of the [[nutrition]]al quality of [[school meal]]s in his TV documentary ''[[Jamie's School Dinners]]'' and the recommendations of the School Meals Review Panel. It had been found that standards of school food were low, with average ingredient spend per meal before 2005 at secondary schools at around 40p. [[Childhood obesity]] is a problem in the UK in specific demographic groups (see [[National Statistics Socio-economic Classification]]), with some medical professionals predicting that today's youngsters will have a lower life expectancy than their parents with problems with [[diabetes]] and [[heart disease]].
Suzi Leather was appointed as Chair of the Trust and Judy Hargadon, an NHS senior manager, was appointed as the Trust's first Chief Executive. Leather resigned in 2006 to become Chair of the Charity Commission and, in November of that year, [[Prue Leith]] was named as the Chair.<ref>{{cite news|author=Alexandra Smith |url=http://education.guardian.co.uk/schoolmeals/story/0,,1943553,00.html |title=Prue Leith to head healthy school meals campaign |publisher=Education Guardian |date=9 November 2006 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref> She retired in January 2010. Hargadon retired in 2013 and was succeeded by Linda Cregan. <ref>https://www.thecaterer.com/articles/346886/judy-hargadon-to-step-down-from-childrens-food-trust-role</ref>
In April 2007, the Trust also became a registered charity.<ref name=cc-1118995>{{EW charity|1118995}}</ref> In October 2011, the Trust officially ceased to be an NDPB,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.gov.uk/inthenews/pressnotices/a0065273/dfe-to-close-arms-length-bodies-to-improve-accountability |title=Department for Education announcement: DfE to close arm's length bodies to improve accountability |publisher=Department for Education |date=14 October 2010 |accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref> expanding its work both as a charity and by trading its services through a new community interest company, as the Children's Food Trust.
In July 2017 the charity's closure was announced due to running out of funding<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-40706184|title=Funds loss closes child food charity|date=2017-07-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the charity was officially closed on 30th September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.childrensfoodtrust.org.uk/blog/childrens-food-trust-leaves-fitting-legacy-as-it-passes-on-the-baton/|title=Children’s Food Trust leaves fitting legacy as it passes on the baton - Childrens Food Trust|date=2017-09-28|work=Childrens Food Trust|access-date=2017-10-13|language=en-GB}}</ref>
==Funding== The trust was initially funded by a [[Pound sterling|£]]15 million grant from the Department for Education and Skills, and has been awarded in partnership with organisations including [[The Prince's Trust]], Business in the Community, Magic Outcomes and the Improvement Foundation, £20 million additional funding from the [[Big Lottery Fund]] for a network of school children's cookery clubs called Let's Get Cooking.<ref>{{cite web|author=Chris Druce |url=http://www.caterersearch.com/Articles/2007/02/23/311846/school-food-trust-looks-to-national-lottery-for-cookery-club.htm |title=School Food Trust looks to National Lottery for cookery club funding |publisher=Caterer Search |date=23 February 2007 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref>
