{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Iron poisoning | synonym = iron toxicity, iron overdose | image = | width = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | onset = | duration = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''Iron poisoning''' is an [[iron overload]] caused by a large excess of [[iron]] intake and usually refers to an acute overload rather than a gradual one. The term has been primarily associated with young children<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Infantile iron poisoning: Challenges in diagnosis and management|url = http://content.wkhealth.com/linkback/openurl?sid=WKPTLP:landingpage&an=00130478-200905000-00040|journal = Pediatric Critical Care Medicine|pages = e31-e33|volume = 10|issue = 3|doi = 10.1097/pcc.0b013e318198b0c2|first = Kevin|last = Valentine|first2 = Christopher|last2 = Mastropietro|first3 = Ashok P.|last3 = Sarnaik}}</ref> who consumed large quantities of [[iron supplement]] pills, which resemble sweets and are widely used, including by pregnant women; approximately 3 grams is lethal for a two-year-old.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ansci.cornell.edu/plants/toxicagents/iron.html |title=Iron Toxicity, What You Don't Know |work=Plants Poisonous to Livestock |publisher=Cornell University Department of Animal Science |date= |accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref> Targeted packaging restrictions in the US for supplement containers with over 250&nbsp;mg elemental iron have existed since 1978, and recommendations for unit packaging have reduced the several iron poisoning fatalities per year to almost zero since 1998.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tenenbein |first=M. |date=June 2005 |title=Unit-Dose Packaging of Iron Supplements and Reduction of Iron Poisoning in Young Children |journal=Arch Pediatr Adolesc Med |volume=159 |pages=557–560 |url=http://archpedi.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/full/159/6/557 |doi=10.1001/archpedi.159.6.557 | pmid = 15939855}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=AAPCC Annual Reports |publisher=American Association of Poison Control Centers |url=http://www.aapcc.org/annual.htm |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080522011517/http://www.aapcc.org/annual.htm |archivedate=2008-05-22 |df= }}</ref> No known cases of iron poisoning have been identified that are associated with [[iron mining]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}
==Signs and symptoms== The first indication of iron poisoning by ingestion is stomach pain, as iron is corrosive to the lining of the gastrointestinal tract, including the stomach. Nausea and vomiting are also common symptoms and [[hematemesis|bloody vomiting]] may occur. The pain then abates for 24 hours as the iron passes deeper into the body, resulting in [[metabolic acidosis]], which in turn damages internal organs, particularly the [[brain]] and the [[liver]]. Iron poisoning can cause [[hypovolemic shock]] due to iron's potent ability to [[vasodilation|dilate the blood vessels]].{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} Death may occur from [[liver failure]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2012}}
If intake of iron is for a prolonged period of time, symptoms are likely to be similar to other causes of [[iron overload]].
==Cause== {{main|Iron}} In nature, iron is usually found in its oxidized form, [[iron (III) oxide]], which is insoluble. Ferrous iron, iron (II), is soluble and its toxicity varies, largely with the integrity of the gastrointestinal lining. Iron supplements are typically used to treat [[anemia]]. Modalities include: diet, parasite control,<ref>{{cite web |vauthors=Stoltzfus RJ, Dreyfuss ML |title=Guidelines for the Use of Iron Supplements to Prevent and Treat Iron Deficiency Anemia |date=2000 |publisher=International Nutritional Anemia Consultative Group, International Life Sciences Institute Press |url=http://www.ilsi.org/file/b2_VUHUQ8AK.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref> [[vitamin A]], [[riboflavin]] (B<sub>2</sub>),<ref>{{cite journal |author=Allen LH |title=Iron Supplements: Scientific Issues Concerning Efficacy and Implications for Research and Programs |journal=J. Nutr. |volume=132 |issue=4 |pages=813S–9S |date=April 2002 |pmid=11925487 |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/cgi/content/full/132/4/813S}}</ref> [[vitamin C]] (for absorption), [[folate]](B<sub>9</sub>), [[Vitamin B12|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]] and multivitamin-multimineral supplements,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/health/dci/Diseases/anemia/anemia_all.html |title=What Is Anemia? |publisher=National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services |date=18 May 2012 }}</ref> with or without iron; potentially avoiding the use of iron only supplements.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hemochromatosis and Anemia Diet |publisher=Iron Overload Diseases Association |url=http://www.ironoverload.org/Diet.html}}</ref>
===Toxic dose=== The amount of iron ingested may give a clue to potential toxicity. The therapeutic dose for iron deficiency anemia is 3–6&nbsp;mg/kg/day. Toxic effects begin to occur at doses above 10–20&nbsp;mg/kg of elemental iron. Ingestions of more than 50&nbsp;mg/kg of elemental iron are associated with severe toxicity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/iron-poisoning |title=Iron Poisoning |publisher=Webmd.com |date= |accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref>
* A 325-mg tablet of ferrous sulfate heptahydrate has 65&nbsp;mg (20%) of elemental iron * A 325-mg tablet of ferrous gluconate has 39&nbsp;mg (12%) of elemental iron * A 325-mg tablet of ferrous fumarate has 107.25&nbsp;mg (33%) of elemental iron * 200&nbsp;mg ferrous sulfate, dried, has 65&nbsp;mg (33%) of elemental iron
In terms of [[blood values]], iron levels above 350–500 [[microgram|µg]]/dL are considered toxic, and levels over 1000&nbsp;µg/dL indicate severe iron poisoning.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iron Tests |date= |work= |publisher=The Free Dictionary by Falex |url=http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/Iron+Tests}} citing: Gale Encyclopedia of Medicine. Copyright 2008</ref>
==Diagnosis== A detail history of the ingestion especially the number of pills taken can be vital. Diagnosis of iron poisoning can be made in the absence of a specific history by clinical judgment, imagining investigation and lab assessment. Iron tablets may be imaged by radiography. Serum iron levels can be tested and are useful regarding the administration of iron-binding ligands such as deferoxamine. Clinic presentation in the absence of treatment follows in stages and is dose dependent (how much iron was taken):,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/54913574|title=Pediatrics|date=2005|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|others=Brown, Lloyd J., Miller, Lee T. (Lee Todd)|isbn=9780781721295|location=Philadelphia|oclc=54913574}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uptodate.com/contents/approach-to-the-child-with-occult-toxic-exposure?search=approuch+to+the+child+with+occult+toxic+exposure&source=search_result&selectedTitle=1~150|title=Approach to the child with occult toxic exposure|website=www.uptodate.com|access-date=2018-01-04}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" |'''Stage''' |'''Time Post Ingestion''' |'''Signs''' |'''Symptoms''' |- |1 |1 – 6 Hours |[[Vomiting]], [[Diarrhea]], [[Gastrointestinal bleeding|GI Bleeding]], [[Circulatory shock]] from hemorrhage and vasodilation |Abdominal Pain |- |2 |6 – 12 hours |Possible resolution of some signs based on treatment and dosage of poisoning |Resolution of Symptoms (considered a dangerous period if severe poisoning but if mild then may indicate a true turning point) |- |3 |12 – 36 hours |[[Metabolic acidosis]], [[Circulatory collapse]], [[Hepatic failure]]
[[Renal failure]]
[[Disseminated intravascular coagulation|D.I.C.]]
Neurologic decline | |- |4 |2 – 6 weeks |Signs of [[fibrosis]] at the [[Pylorus|pyloric]] region and elsewhere in the intestine with concomitant stenosis (narrowing) | |}
==Treatment== Later stage treatment consists of [[Chelation therapy|cleaning the iron from the blood]], using a [[chelating agent]] such as [[deferoxamine]]. If this fails then [[dialysis]] is the next step.
